<i>Posted by Numbuk on 08-14-2000 11:57 PM:</i>

<p><b><img src="images/icons/Book.gif" alt="" width="15" height="15" border="0"> </b></p>

<p><i>Dis is Numbuk's first attempt at writing epic story.  It especially Numbuk's first attempt at writing story from an ogre perspective.  Me will <b>try</b> to update dis story every day or so, so keep checking back.<br>
<br>
Please no reply to dis thread, so it make it easier to read from chapter to chapter.  If yous have any comments, suggestions, or anyting about dis story, please post it in <a href="http://forums.interealms.com/ranger/showthread.php?threadid=26058" target="_blank">Dis Thread</a>.<br>
<br>
Me hope yous enjoy dis story as much as me is writing it.<br>
<br>
Oh, and me never really been writer before, so grammar stink.  But hey, me is an ogre, so cut some slack!</i><br>
<br>
<br>
<b>Chapter 1.</b><br>
<br>
<br>
In a small cave in Oggok dere lived a nice ogre family.  Like many ogre families, dey had a mommy, a daddy, and two boy ogres.  Dis family was da Emgood family and dey were a happy bunch.  Smash was da older brudder and he would play "How Many Lumps Can I Make Yous Head Get" with younger brother Bash.<br>
<br>
Dis was a happy time.  Daddy Emgood would fish all day long and sell his wares to the shopkeepers.  Mommy Emgood would spend her days dirtying up da unsightly "clean spots" in da cave and make her usual Froglok Booger Pie.  All was going berry well, until one night.<br>
<br>
"How was yous day, Bash?" asked Daddy Emgood while his family was sitting at da dinner table.<br>
<br>
"It fun!" said Bash excitedly.  "Smash gave me record number of lumps on head!  He gave me 14!  At least, dat what he say.  But me tink he no can count good."<br>
<br>
"Shut up," growled Smash, "Yous is just a dumbhead!  Me give yous more tomorrow!"<br>
<br>
"Now be quiet both of yous," barked Mommy Emgood.  "Don't make me have to give you both baths!"<br>
<br>
Both young ogres immediately slammed deir mouths shut and began eating quietly.  Nothing was heard but da sound of chomping and slurping.  Nothing, until da cave door exploded into a pile of smoldering rubble.<br>
<br>
Da Emgood family looked up with a shock.  Standing at da door was a mean looking goblin wizard.  Hand still smoking from some spell, he pointed a finger at Daddy Emgood.<br>
<br>
"Ah ha!  So you're the one I've been hunting for all these years!" da goblin cackled gleefully.  "Now I've found you, and now you shall die!"<br>
<br>
Without another word, da wizard sent two fireballs hurling into da Emgood family.  It hit both Mommy and Daddy Emgood and dey disappeared into a cloud of smoke and ash.  Bash and Smash just look on in disbelief and horror.  The goblin just smiles and blows on his finger.<br>
<br>
"That takes care of that," da goblin said. "No more worrying about that ogre coming to slay me."<br>
<br>
"Yous dumbhead," Bash yelled out sobbing.  "He was good ogre!  He no wanted to kill anyone but gnomes, frogloks, orcs, bears, lizards, giants, treants, mammoths, sarnaks, skeletons, zombies, beetles, griffins, and dorfs.  He no wanted to kill goblin magic ting!"<br>
<br>
"Ah, but he would have," said the goblin.  "He was prophecied to kill me, so I just did the deed first.  Prophecy speaks of an ogre who will be my downfall, and I have tracked him to this house.  And by process of elimination, I figured it was your dad since you two are both too small and your mother was just a female.  So you see, now I can be safe."<br>
<br>
"Me tink yous is telling us too much information," said Smash.  "But why did yous kills our mudder too?"  Smash's eyes started to well up in tears.<br>
<br>
"I've nothing to fear from telling you too much information," remarked da goblin snidely.  "You're just kids!  As for your mother, well, I just happened to miss with my first fireball and hitting her was an accident.  Oh well, nobody's perfect."<br>
<br>
"Yous name is... Smellybreath?  Or is dat just a trait?" asked Bash inquisitively.<br>
<br>
"It is both a name and a trait.  How did you know it was my name?"<br>
<br>
"Yous have a sticker on yous chest dat say, 'Hello!  My name is Smellybreath' with words 'A.A. Meeting' at bottom."<br>
<br>
"Oh.  Right.  I forgot to take that off."<br>
<br>
"Ok den.  We will not forget.  Us is gonna train now for few years and we'll bash yous good!"<br>
<br>
"Good luck with that."  Smellybreath chuckled to himself.  "I'd like to see <b>that</b> happen.  Yeah right!  Take care, you little kids!  I am sure I'll never be seeing you ever again!"<br>
<br>
And with dat, da goblin vanished in a puff of smoke.</p>
<hr>
<i>Posted by Numbuk on 08-15-2000 05:31 AM:</i>

<p><b><img src="images/icons/Embarass_Face.gif" alt="" width="15" height="15" border="0"> </b></p>

<p><b>Chapter 2.</b><br>
<br>
<br>
Bash and Smash never forgot da face of mean goblin who killed deir parents.  Dey never forgot da evil glint in his red eyes, but mostly, dey never forgot his horrible breath.  Dere was a good reason his name was Smellybreath.<br>
<br>
Dey both went and lived with deir ogre grandfather.  Deir granddad was an ogre hippy, so he would always be using "special herbs" and listening to ogre sitar music.  <br>
<br>
Bash and Smash no had need of such tings, and so began to teach demselves da art of combat.  Dey knew dere was more to it dan just picking up big stick and smashing tings wit it, and dey knew it gonna take more dan said stick to bash Smellybreath.  Dey practiced hours on end learning different moves, different swings, even a few shamanistic spells.  Dey did nothing else but practice fighting wit each other.<br>
<br>
Well, until a few years later when dey discovered ogre girls... but let's skip past dat part right now.  Fast forward a few years and us is now on same page.<br>
<br>
"Moondoggy," said Papa Smurpheater while sitting in a meditative pose in da living room, "come on in here child."<br>
<br>
"Grandpa, my name is Bash," Bash said getting tired of reminding his grandfather of what his real name is.  "Me hate name Moondoggy!"<br>
<br>
"Right, right.  Far out, man!  Moondoggy, can you go grab your brother Shroombaby?"<br>
<br>
"Grandpa," said Smash, "Me name no is Shroombaby and me is already here!"<br>
<br>
"Right, right.  Outta Sight!  Feel the love.  The love!  Then cherish the colors.  The colors!"<br>
<br>
Bash and Smash looked at each other and rolled deir eyes.  Dey had been through dis routine before.  Once grandpa got going, he never came back until a few hours later.  Luckily, dis time, he snapped out of it.<br>
<br>
"Whoa!  Trippy.  Now look here, flower children, I have had a revelation this night."<br>
<br>
"Like when you had a revelation dat we should spend adolescence naked wit our names painted on our butts?" Bash asked not all too kindly.<br>
<br>
"Yeah, dat was embarrassing!" excalimed Smash.  "Us still get picked on today!  How about da time yous had a revelation dat lizardmen now like ogres and we should go try and make friends wit dem?"<br>
<br>
"Me still have lizard teeth stuck in me arm!" shouted Bash.<br>
<br>
"Settle down, lovemonkeys," Papa said calmly.  "This hip revelation came from the Sacred Peyote."<br>
<br>
Both brothers just stared in silence.  Papa's revelations were never wrong when he smoked the Sacred Peyote.  It was rumored he had pilfered it from a wizard's spire long ago in his adventuring days.  He rarely touched it, but when he did, his predictions always came true.  Well. most of da time.<br>
<br>
"Now, you should know that one of you isn't going to like this," Papa said with glazed eyes.  "I have had a vision of that goblin you crazy cats always are talking about.  I have had a vision of where he's hiding out, and what you boys are to do about it."<br>
<br>
Both ogres just stared with jaws agape.  Dis was good news.  Dey would do anyting to smash dat dumbhead goblin.  Dey waited intently for da old ogre to continue.<br>
<br>
"It appears," Papa began, "that unrighteous oppressor has been shacking up in a mountain range known as Trakanon's Teeth.  And, my vision has said that only one of you may go to slay him and the other must stay behind.  If it is any other way, then you will both be killed.  Whoever leaves, man, it must be tonight.  And, man, if you don't do the deed within three months, it'll be too late."<br>
<br>
"What do yous mean, 'too late'?" asked Bash.<br>
<br>
"I'm not sure, Moondoggy.  It just says, 'too late.'"<br>
<br>
"It actually say, <i>'too late,'</i>?" Smash interjected.<br>
<br>
"Well, no.  I saw the vision of a donkey skinnydipping in a vat of chocolate ice cream.  We ogre hippies concluded long ago that <i>that</i> particular image means 'too late.'"<br>
<br>
Da young ogres could no deny da wisdom of da ogre hippies of yore.  Dey thought about what deir grandpa had told dem.  Dey thought so hard it make deir heads hurt.  Finally, Smash stood up.<br>
<br>
"Me will go!  Me will go smash goblin!  Me is oldest, and derefore me should be one who goes!"<br>
<br>
Bash didn't like da idea of his brudder on his own and felt confident dat he himself could kill mean old Smellybreath.  But, he and his brother have become almost perfect equals in fighting over the past few years.  He no could argue with his older brudder, and he knew no udder ogre -- udder dan himself -- was suited for da job.<br>
<br>
"Smash," Bash said with tears in eyes, "Me know yous will avenge our parent's death.  Me sure you not gonna fail and den force me to go on adventure of me own.  Make sure yous give dat wizard an extra good bash for me."<br>
<br>
"Me will.  Me promise.  Me will come back and den us will finally be like regular ogres."<br>
<br>
"Shroombaby," Papa said placing his arms on Smash's shoulders, "Take care of yourself.  I have put together a journey pack for you.  It has all the things you will ever need.  Well, it has all the things <b>I</b> ever needed on adventures.  Hurry up and take it and get out of here!"<br>
<br>
With a nod, Smash picked up da ogre backpack off of da floor.  He gave his family each a good, big ogre hug and den opened up da door.  He stepped out into a starlit sky, and jogged off towards the city gates.<br>
<br>
"Me hope he be ok," sniffled Bash.<br>
<br>
"Shroombaby's got a good head on his shoulders.  Nothing's gonna happen to him.  He'll be back before the three months are up.  Man, I've got 'the munchies' something fierce!"<br>
<br>
A year passed by and dey never heard from Smash.</p>
<hr>
<i>Posted by Numbuk on 08-16-2000 07:20 AM:</i>

<p><b> </b></p>

<p><b>Chapter 3.</b><br>
<br>
<br>
Lilting was a young male halfling who grew up in Rivervale with his family.  Like almost all halflings, Lilting was a druid.  His mother was a druid, his father was a druid, and his uncle was a used armor salesman... but we won't speak of dat black sheep of the family.<br>
<br>
On a particularly hot afternoon, Lilting was on da outskirts of town trying various techniques of da druid ways.  Da blond haired halfling liked to try unconventional methods of his magic.  He thought dere was more to being a druid dan what most people tink.  Unfortunately, he just wasn't very good at spell casting at all.  And even more unfortunately, he was a bit clumsy and some would also say a little slow in da head.<br>
<br>
"See that bixie over there?" Lilting asked his halfling buddy who was out wit him dis day.<br>
<br>
"Of course I do," his friend Nappyhair replied wit a hint of irritation.  "It's five feet in front of us!"<br>
<br>
"Well watch this!  Watch how a tried and true method can be used more effectively when reversed!"<br>
<br>
"Whatever," Nappyhair responded not really, caring anymore.<br>
<br>
Lilting began waving his arms around and chanting.  Blue sparks emanating from his fingers, he spoke da magic words. "I call upon the spirits of wolf!  Come to me and enter this bixie!"<br>
<br>
Nappyhair, hardly listening but catching dat last line, snapped his head in Lilting's direction wit pure puzzlement.  <br>
<br>
"Are you sure that you want to do..."<br>
<br>
"Shhh!  Watch!  Trust me," the halfling said as he quickly began casting his second spell.  "Sticky feet come to me, Ensnare my foe and don't let him free!"<br>
<br>
Instead of pointing at da bixie, however, Lilting pointed to himself.  His feet seemed to magically acquire some powerful adhesive dat made it much harder for him to run.<br>
<br>
"Ummm..." is all Nappyhair could say.  He was in complete bewilderment.<br>
<br>
"I call this a 'Reverse Kite.'" Lilting said proudly.  "You see, I figure that if most druids have a hard time when they are sped up and monsters are slowed down, that if the opposite were applied then I should have an easier time with everything.  The theory is sound!"<br>
<br>
"Ummm..." is all Nappyhair could say as he looked at his friend in disbelief.  About dis time, da small bee-like fairy realized what was going on.  It turned and made a mad dash for Lilting.<br>
<br>
"Run!" yelped Nappyhair.  "You've made it mad!"<br>
<br>
"Like I said, don't worry!  My theory will work.  It's been...  OW!"<br>
<br>
Da bixie easily caught up with da slower halfling and stung him right in da arm.  Even da bixie couldn't believe how stupid dis particular halfling was.  Realizing dat maybe his idea might not be as brilliant as he had thought, Lilting opted to do what druids do best:  Run away like mad.<br>
<br>
"Let's get out of here!  Ow!  Ow!" Lilting said turning to his friend, but Nappyhair had long since bolted away.  Lilting started to make a run for his home, but it was slow-going because of his ensnare spell.<br>
<br>
<br>
********<br>
<br>
<br>
Back in Rivervale, an out-of-breath Nappyhair explained to Lilting's parents what happened.<br>
<br>
"What are we to do with our son?" asked Mama Lildruid.  "He doesn't seem to want to learn our ways."<br>
<br>
"I guess we'll just have to punish him.  Again." Daddy Lildruid was disappointed his only son wouldn't learn da art of being a druid.  "How far behind you was he, Nappyhair?"<br>
<br>
"Well, uh," stammered Nappyhair, "I think he, uh, was right behind me."<br>
<br>
Suddenly a faint noise could be heard coming from just outside da city gates.  "Ow!"  It progressively became louder.  "Ow!"  Many halflings exited deir homes to see what dis noise was and crowded around the center of da town.<br>
<br>
Coming over da ridge, a very stung and very slow Lilting jogged towards his parents.  Just behind him was da mean bixie who kept stinging his backside.  "Ow!  Ow!  Ow!  Ow!"  Lilting kept yelping.<br>
<br>
Daddy Lildruid came to da rescue and swatted da bixie away.  "Get out of here!"  Da bixie just made a laughing, buzzing sound at Lilting and left da way it came.<br>
<br>
"Now, young man," Daddy Lildruid began, "What were you thinking?!"<br>
<br>
"I wanted to try..."<br>
<br>
"You wanted to get yourself killed!" Mama Lildruid scolded.  "Why do you have to try different things?  We're druids!  We cast, and then we run away!  We cast again, and then we run away again!  Anything else is suicide!"<br>
<br>
Da gathered crowd of halfling villagers all nodded deir agreement at what da boy's mother had said.  Dis was da art of kiting first invented by da halfling legend, Kiter McTerrified.<br>
<br>
"Son," his father told Lilting sternly while placing a hand on his shoulder, "I'm going to have to punish you until you learn.  No supper for you tonight."<br>
<br>
"Nooooo!!!  Dad, please, no!  Anything but that!  Anything!"<br>
<br>
"Hold on, I say, Hold on here!"  A voice from da crowd rose up.  A halfling pushed his way through da crowd.  He was older dan da rest of da halflings, fatter too.  "Now what is, I say, what is the problem here?"<br>
<br>
"Mayor McFurrybottom!"  Daddy Lildruid said in astonishment.  "There's no problem.  Well, nothing too big.  It's my son, your honor.  He rejects our standard druid ways and tried a new fighting tactic.  He trained a bixie into town."<br>
<br>
"Is that so?  Bixies, eh?  Nasty little, I say, nasty little buggers.  Can't have them running around town.  Certainly not."  Da crowd of halflings shook deir heads in agreement, wit several others repeating "Certainly not."<br>
<br>
"None of you understand," Lilting began, "I feel that druids are capable of much more than what we know!  I think that we can become one of the land's most respected people and not just a running gag!"<br>
<br>
"Nonsense, my boy," da Mayor said in disbelief,  "We druids have survived hundreds of years by holding dear to the truths and teachings of our beloved Kiter McTerrified!  We will continue to do for hundreds of years more.  Running away is what we do best!"<br>
<br>
"Well, maybe I'm tired of running away!" Lilting said wit tears of anger and frustration welling up inside him.  "Maybe I want to use a weapon now and then!"<br>
<br>
Mama Lildruid snapped a hand up to her mouth in utter horror at what her son had just said.  Da crowd of halflings gasped in shock and began whispering amongst demselves.<br>
<br>
"Maybe I want to actually use spells like thorn skin!" Lilting said defiantly.<br>
<br>
Mama Lildruid's second hand snapped up to her mouth.   Louder gasps and whispers came from da crowd.<br>
<br>
"And maybe I want to shave my foot hair from time to time!"<br>
<br>
Mama Lildruid's eyes rolled back into her head and she fainted.  Daddy Lildruid could stand to hear no more. <br>
<br>
"Blasphemy!" said Daddy.  "Son, I'm going to pretend I didn't hear that!  I'm going to pretend the bee stings on your backside are causing you to think irrationally!  Look what you did to your mother! Go to your room this instant!"<br>
<br>
"One more thing, dad." said Lilting.  "Maybe I want to actually join a group when I go out fighting."<br>
<br>
"That's it, boy," Mayor McFurrybottom said wit a finger pointed straight at Lilting, "You're a bad seed.  Thoughts like that will destroy this town!  You bring a nasty bixie here today, what will you bring tomorrow with these foolhardy ideas?  A bear?  A giant?!  I hearby decree that you shall be banned from this city for a period of no less than 3 months!  If being out on your own doesn't teach you that our ways are the correct ways, nothing will!"<br>
<br>
"Sir, I..."<br>
<br>
"Go!" da mayor pointed towards da gates of da city.  Da crowd all nodded in agreement with the mayor.  Each halfling had a scowl on their face and waited impatiently for Lilting to leave.<br>
<br>
"Son," Daddy Lildruid said wit restraint, "I think this is for the best.  Please do as the Mayor says.  And please remember our teachings.  They will keep you alive.  Don't be a fool and try to change them.  Now, please go.  Your mother and I will await your return."<br>
<br>
"Dad, I just..."<br>
<br>
"Please, son.  For your mother, for me, for yourself.  Just go."<br>
<br>
And without another word, Lilting turned around and slowly walked out of Rivervale.</p>
<hr>
<i>Posted by Numbuk on 08-18-2000 11:10 PM:</i>

<p><b><img src="images/icons/icon5.gif" alt="Question" width="15" height="15" border="0"> </b></p>

<p><b>Chapter 4.</b><br>
<br>
<br>
It was da middle of da night and all was silent in Oggok.  Well, all was silent except for all da loud snoring coming from every single ogre cave in dat town, and da loud scraping sound made whenever da guards needed to scratch demselves.  Udder dan dat dough, all was quiet.<br>
<br>
On his bed dat was made of a big slab of rock, Bash slept uneasily.  He always had nightmares of what he feared may have happened to Smash on his journey.  It had been a year since he saw him last and Bash worried he may no have killed Smellybreath.<br>
<br>
A very loud *THUD* woke Bash up with startle.  Bash looked over to see Papa Smurpheater on da floor cursing someting about it being too dark during night time.<br>
<br>
"Grandpa!" said Bash as he jumped out bed to help da old ogre up. "Is yous ok?  What you doing in me room dis late?"<br>
<br>
Grandpa rubbed da side of his face for a few seconds and den spoke.  "Well, Moondoggy, I wake up because I had the munch...er.. I was hungry.  So I stumble into the kitchen to grab a bite to eat.  Well, I accidentally grabbed the Sacred Peyote and didn't know it.  I took a huge bite and swallowed it down."<br>
<br>
Bash hoped his grandpa wasn't going to die.  He never seen him so sick and wobbly before.<br>
<br>
"The funny thing is," said Papa, "I found out that I've been using the Sacred Peyote wrong all these years.  You're not supposed to smoke it!  It was a groovy experience, man."<br>
<br>
"Well, what happened?!"<br>
<br>
"Hmmm... let me think... it's all a little fuzzy.  Well, naturechild, I think your brother's not coming back anytime soon.  And I think he may even be in danger.  The Details are a bit funny.  I do know this though:  You must go to Halas."<br>
<br>
"Halas?!" Bash said in complete shock.  "But dat is farthest away place of anywhere in dis world!  What is me supposed to do dere?!  Buy a kilt?!"<br>
<br>
"Settle down, hip cat."  Papa said wit his hands raised.  "You need to head to that land of uncool coldness to talk the one person who can tell you where to find your brother."<br>
<br>
"And who would dat be?"<br>
<br>
"I have no idea.  I just know he's hanging around Halas.  That's what my vision said."<br>
<br>
"And is dat all?"<br>
<br>
"No, it said that if you find people willing to help you along your journey, that you should let them.  Maybe even go out of your way to ask a few people.  If I had not smoked the Peyote last time, I bet the same would have applied to your brother.  Stupid me.  I should have realized that trying to solo in this world is the second dumbest thing there is."<br>
<br>
"What's da first dumbest ting?"<br>
<br>
"Answering a female ogre when she asks, 'Do yous tink me hips look fatter now dan before?' instead of running away.  There is no way to answer that question without getting several broken bones."<br>
<br>
"Hmmm.  Me remember dat.  Is dat all da visions yous had?"<br>
<br>
"Yep.  Well, after all that I did have a good conversation with a purple camel and a very foul-mouthed rock.  But it wasn't anything important.  Something about 'A Banshee and sock puppets.'"<br>
<br>
"Ok den.  Me will leave in da morning for Halas.  Me was having good dream about dat cute ogre girl in da Shaman guild."<br>
<br>
"No no!  You have to leave tonight!"<br>
<br>
"Why?"<br>
<br>
"Because that was part of my vision."<br>
<br>
"You said dat was all..."<br>
<br>
"Yeah yeah.  Shut up.  You have to leave tonight or else..."<br>
<br>
"...Da donkey and da ice cream?"<br>
<br>
"You got it."  Papa reached into his tunic and pulled out some coins. "Here, take these and buy some food for your journey.  And also..."<br>
<br>
Papa walked to the other end of the room and opened up a secret, false-rock panel.  He pulled out a gigantic, gold-plated mallet.<br>
<br>
"I want you to take this.  I should have given it to your brother, but I was too stoned to remember it.  This hammer has seen many adventuring days in our family and has squished many an orc head.  It is said that if the right ogre were to ever wield it...  Ah, I can't remember the rest."<br>
<br>
Bash's eyes were wide open, staring at da most beautiful hammer he ever seen.  He thought he was not worthy of such a ting.<br>
<br>
"Grandpa... me... me no can take dis."<br>
<br>
"Yes you can, and yes you will.  I can't smoke it, so what good does it do me anymore?  Besides, you may need it for some nasty, harrowing, climactic escape or battle.  Now, get out here.  There's little time to waste!"<br>
<br>
Bash gently took da mallet from Papa's hands with awe and reverence.  He den hugged his grandfather and left da house he and his brudder had been raised in for several years.  Bash stopped at da 24 hour ogre store near da Oggok entrance to buy some rations and den set off on his journey.<br>
<br>
Bash jogged down da road dat lead southeast in da Feerrott swamp.  Swatting at buzzing mosquitoes and stomping on da occasional snake for fun, he made good time.  An hour or so down da road he noticed dat da sun was starting to come up. <br>
<br>
Bash stopped as he saw a small lizard camp dat he knew well.  He saw da three lizardmen warming demselves around a fire dat he and Smash used to beat upon to help demselves train.  He smiled.<br>
<br>
Da lizardmen all looked up at da same time and saw Bash wit a wicked grin on his face.  Den dey saw da big, golden hammer da ogre was carrying.  Dey looked at each udder, and den dey immediately scattered in all directions to hide from da ogre dey remembered all-too-well.<br>
<br>
Bash frowned.  Da lizards no wanted to play.  He sighed and prepared to continue onward, but he heard a noise come from somewhere above him.<br>
<br>
"I'm a tree!  I'm a tree!  I'm a..." Da snapping and cracking of a branch was heard shortly after da voice was interrupted.<br>
<br>
Bash scratched his head in puzzlement and a few seconds later he saw a blond halfling fall from da sky and land wit a loud *THUMP* in front of him.</p>
<hr>
<i>Posted by Numbuk on 08-21-2000 10:35 PM:</i>

<p><b><img src="images/icons/Laughing_Face.gif" alt="" width="15" height="15" border="0"> </b></p>

<p><b>Chapter 5.</b><br>
<br>
<br>
Bash looked at da unconscious halfling dat lay in front of him on da forest road.  He said many 'tank yous' to his god, Da Warlord, for giving him such a fine meal dis day.  He bent over and picked up da halfling, opened his mouth and prepared to take a big bite.<br>
<br>
Da halfling awoke just as his little head was inside da big ogre's mouth.  A muffled scream came from inside Bash's throat.<br>
<br>
"Pleesh donf eaf mef!!!"<br>
<br>
Bash pulled da halfling out of his mouth.  "What did yous call me?!"<br>
<br>
"I said," the frightened halfling stammered, "'Please don't eat me!'"<br>
<br>
"Why?  Yous look like a good meal.  Me is hungry.  Me have long journey ahead of me and me need da protein."<br>
<br>
"But...  But I can help you!"  The halfling would do anything at this point to get out of being eaten.  "You need someone to carry that big hammer for you on your journey?  You need someone to help you fight whatever it is you need fighting?  You need anyone to slay some mean wizards or someth..."<br>
<br>
"Wizards?  What yous know about wizards?"  Bash was intrigued.  Maybe he stumbled upon a ting who knew where Smellybreath was.<br>
<br>
"Nothing other than they use magic.  I was just saying I could help..."<br>
<br>
Den again, maybe not.  But Bash remembered what his grandpa said about letting peoples join his group if he meet peoples who is willing.  He decided to give it a shot.<br>
<br>
"Ok den.  Yous can come along wit me and me will no eat yous.  Me name is Bash Emgood."<br>
<br>
"Great!" The halfling became excited and relieved at the same time.  Maybe Lilting will be able to do something to prove dat druids is more dan what everyone tinks on dis journey.  "My name is Lilting.  So where are we headed and what are we doing when we get there?"<br>
<br>
"Us is going to Halas.  And when we get dere, us is looking for a person me grandpa told me about who can tell us where me brudder is so us can find a goblin who bashed our parents and den bash it and come back and be done."<br>
<br>
Lilting just blinked in confusion.<br>
<br>
"Us is going to Halas."<br>
<br>
"Ok!  Well, let's get going!  I hope you don't have anything against druids because I am one."<br>
<br>
Bash's urge to eat da halfling resurfaced.  He did his best to stifle it.  <i>At least</i>, Bash thought, <i>he'll be able to haul his little butt away from any danger.  Me will no have to protect him too much.  Dat is good.</i><br>
<br>
"However," Lilting began, "I'm not like most druids.  I don't believe in using the same tactics every other druid employs."<br>
<br>
<i>So much for dat.</i><br>
<br>
"Well, let's get going!" the enthusiastic halfling excalimed excitedly.  "Can I carry that big hammer of yours?"<br>
<br>
"No."<br>
<br>
"Can I ride on your shoulders?"<br>
<br>
"No."<br>
<br>
"Can I sing some traveling songs?"<br>
<br>
"No."<br>
<br>
"Can I pick fights with everything that passes us by because you'll pound them?"<br>
<br>
"No."<br>
<br>
"Can I..."<br>
<br>
Da questions of da halfling trailed off as dey headed east towards da murky, foul, Innothule Swamp.<br>
<br>
<br>
