<p><b><img src="images/icons/Embarass_Face.gif" alt="" width="15" height="15" border="0"> </b></p>

<p><b>Chapter 21.</b><br>
<br>
<br>
At da brink of dawn, da party went to go cross da Karana bridge.  Da construction crew had a fun time using cranes and lifts to get each person over, especially da big ogre.  But, it was accomplished in da end.<br>
<br>
"So dis is da 'Dreaded Southern Karana', huh?" asked Bash to no one in particular.  "It not look so bad to me."<br>
<br>
It was true.  Da sun was shining in da eastern horizon, birds were singing.  It was berry nice.  At least, until dey took deir first steps off da bridge and onto da grass itself.  Da second da ogre's foot touched soil, da sky darkened and down came da rain.<br>
<br>
"Me take it back," muttered da ogre.<br>
<br>
"Let's hurry and search the river's edge for signs of Lilting before they get washed away from the rain!" Treehugger said.  "If they disappear, we've got no chance of finding him.  Us rangers are the masters of tracking, but we suck at it.  How's that for irony?"<br>
<br>
"We could ask a druid to track him down if we  can't find him," said Pyra.<br>
<br>
Da party agreed dat dey would rather live with a lost friend dan deal wit anudder druid.<br>
<br>
Treehugger was off in an instant racing eastward along da side of da riverbank.  Da group followed soon after.  Not too far down da ranger came to a dead halt.<br>
<br>
Catching up to him, da group saw da ranger paused still in his tracks.  <br>
<br>
"What's wrong?" whispered Medsa.<br>
<br>
"Shhhh," said Treehugger.  "I hear something.  It's like the sound of a thousand miniature horses walking the field." The ranger frowned.  "Erm, don't ask how I know that."<br>
<br>
Da ranger signaled da group to follow him and he went south a little ways.  Beyond some trees dey saw what caused all da noise.<br>
<br>
Walking in a southern direction was a wood elf wit his held head high.  Behind him, several thousand peoples silently followed him.  Humans, elves, half-elves, all different sizes, but each wearing green.  Most were sniffling or shedding some tears.  All, but da leading wood elf.<br>
<br>
Treehugger bowed his head in respect.  He seemed to know who da elf was.<br>
<br>
"Who is dat?" asked Bash?<br>
<br>
"The Glademaster," Treehugger solemnly replied.  "The greatest ranger that ever walked Norrath, it is said.  His time in this world is up and he goes to give his life essence back to the forest."<br>
<br>
Bash looked at da elf.  He no could see what da fuss was about, but kept quiet out of respect.  Dis elf didn't seem as wussy as udder wood elves, he was sure.<br>
<br>
"Glademaster, eh?" said Yessir wit raised eyebrow.  "Sounds like some sort of gardening tool."<br>
<br>
"The Glademaster, it is rumored, has slain over a thousand banshees.  It is said he is immune to their wailing cries.  He has done much for our forests and our heritage."<br>
<br>
Da elf and da thousands of peoples following him marched off into da distance.<br>
<br>
"Come, let's continue our search for the halfling," Treehugger said wiping a tear away.<br>
<br>
Da group was once again following Treehugger along da riverside.  Bash couldn't see how da ranger was paying attention to details at such a pace, but he was somewhat sure da ranger knew what he was doing.<br>
<br>
After a time, da ranger stopped and squatted down to get a better look at someting on da riverbank.<br>
<br>
Da group caught up wit da ranger and looked to see what he was examining.<br>
<br>
Dere, in da sticky mud, was da impprint of a halfling sprawled out face first.<br>
<br>
