<i>Posted by Numbuk on 10-26-2000 09:06 PM:</i>

<p><b><img src="images/icons/icon6.gif" alt="Cool" width="15" height="15" border="0"> [b]Chapter 34.[/b]</b></p>

<p>Bash stood before two massive, arched, swinging doors interlocked wit each udder.  Da doors were at least fifty feet high.  Dey appeared to be made of da same material as da cavern walls, but dey obviously stood out from da surroundings.  Bash no could feel anyting but awe in front of da huge doors.<br>
<br>
"Prepare yourself for a sight that few have ever seen... and lived to tell about it." said da Glacier bear who was standing alongside da ogre.  Da bear padded up to da doors and stuck it's nose on one of da doors.  Both doors began creaking and groaning as da heavy weight of da two structures began shifting and swinging inward.  Da noise from da doors was berry loud and Bash could feel da whole cave floor shaking beneath his feet.<br>
<br>
Bright light spilled in from da opening slit in da middle of da doors.  As da doors opened wider, more light filled da cavern in which Bash stood.  Da ogre had to squint against da luminous white dat spewed forth from da gigantic entrance.<br>
<br>
Da doors eventually came to a halt when dey swung as wide as dey could.  Da whole caves shook violently from da massive slam da doors made against da walls, but da bear seemed unconcerned.  Bash guessed it would take more dan dat to collapse dese caves.<br>
<br>
"Follow me, young ogre." da bear said solemnly.  It bowed its head and sauntered slowly into da bright room.  Da bear den loudly said, "Miragul!  I will require your assistance."<br>
<br>
Da gold-ish skeleton appeared from around a corner behind Bash and ran at full speed into da room behind da bear.  Da two disappeared into da light.<br>
<br>
Bash gripped his hammer tightly in his right hand and used his left arm to shield his eyes from da blinding light.  He den walked in after da bear.<br>
<br>
Once inside, Bash's eyes adjusted quickly.  Da light no seemed as bright in da room.  Da room was da biggest room Bash ever saw.  He no could see da udder end of da room, it was so big.  Everywhere Bash looked, he saw golden objects of all shapes and sizes.  Some floating, some not.  Some with light magically cascading up and down dem, some not.  Dere were armors, swords, axes, shields, moneys, and a big stockpile of toilet paper.<br>
<br>
But da ting dat drew Bash's full attention, da ting dat made his heart skip a beat for some reason, was da big fountain in da middle of all da golden objects.  It was an octagonal shaped pool dat was eighty feet wide wit crystal clear water.  No color.  Just pure transparency.  Out from da middle of da pool sprayed a fountain dat shot at least ninety feet straight up.  <br>
<br>
From each point at da edge of da pool rose a hollow, see-through column.  Eight ramps ran from da middle of da pool down to da columns.  On top of each column was a piece of da most beautiful armor Bash ever saw.  Gauntlets, leggings, boots, yous name it.  Each was da color of when gold kissed silver -- da color of platinum.  Dey hovered each column, spinning ever so slightly.  Da water from da fountain collected into each ramp and it flowed down into each column underneath each armor piece.  Light bounced against da water and appeared to be giving life to da armors.  It was da most beautiful ting Bash ever saw.  It brought a tear to his eye.<br>
<br>
"As you can see," said da bear quietly, "There are three columns with some armor pieces missing.  They were gifts to another such as yourself hundreds of years ago.  They have long since been lost." <br>
<br>
Da bear paused for a moment.  "But that does not mean more cannot be made.  Miragul..."<br>
<br>
Da lich bounded up beside da bear.  Bash heard anudder set of skeleton footprints and turned to see Jakontiklarkiak jog up beside his friend, Miragul.<br>
<br>
Da glacier bear den started to shake himself violently, as if in were drenched wit water.   Tiny, white hairs flew from its beautiful coat.  Da lich waved his hand and dey all floated to da skeleton.  Da skeleton gathered da furball up and den walked over to da fountain.<br>
<br>
Miragul's jaw moved as if it were talking, den it waved its free hand over da pool.  Da pool turned from crystal color to emerald green.  Da room changed color as well, and Bash realized da light was coming from da fountain.  Miragul dropped da bear's fur into da fountain.  <br>
<br>
Da fountain den glowed so brightly dat Bash no could watch.  He shieled his face wit both arms.  A second later, da light faded.  Bash looked up and saw dat hovering atop one of da empty columns was now a platinum helmet wit three horns in a row, from front to back, in da center.<br>
<br>
"These pieces," said da bear, "Make up the true Totemic Armor.  The true armor of the Pure Shaman.  Few exist today, but one who's heart is true and just may find himself with such a set someday.  You, Bash, are one of those few."<br>
<br>
"But... but me is just a fighter.  Me no is..."<br>
<br>
"Your heart tells me what you are.  You just have not realized it."  Da bear looked at da fountain and sighed.  "I wish I could give you the breastplate as well.  But, I have not the component I need.  Grizzleknot bark is so hard to come by these days, what with all the friggin' druids."  Da bear muttered someting under his breath.<br>
<br>
Bash recalled Lilting in Southern Karana.  He remembered grabbing him and pulling from his mouth...<br>
<br>
"Is dis what yous need?" asked Bash as he pulled out a piece  of bark from his make-shift-from-a-shrub shorts.<br>
<br>
Da bear looked at what Bash held.  It den seemed to smile (as much as a bear can look like it can smile) and den said, "Yes!  Throw it in!"<br>
<br>
Da fountain changed colors again, dis time to a royal blue.  Da room, again, changed colors as well.  Da bright light appeared once more and den da fountain was back to a crystal white color.  Dis time, a gleaming breastplate was now above anudder column.<br>
<br>
"Wow..." whispered Bash.  "Mr. Bear, uh sir, what about dat last column?  What goes dere?"<br>
<br>
"Oh that?  Well...  hey, you know, your mallet looks a little dirty."<br>
<br>
Bash looked at his hammer.  It's golden tint glinting brightly in da crystal light from da fountain.  Bash looked confused.<br>
<br>
"It looks dirty, Bash.  Dip it into the water to clean it."<br>
<br>
Bash no wanted to argue wit a bear.  He walked up to da fountain's edge and plunged his hammer into da transparent water.  As he did so, he watched da gold from his hammer melt away in da water.  It washed off as if it were mud.  Bash slowly pulled his bashing mallet out and it now gleamed da same platinum color as da armor.<br>
<br>
Miragul and Jakontiklarkiak applauded enthusiastically wit deir bony hands.<br>
<br>
"And there you go," said da bear.  "Now, for the test.  Miragul!"<br>
<br>
Da lich nodded.  It waved its hands and all da armor pieces from da fountain lifted up into da air.<br>
<br>
"Do not be afraid, young shaman." said da bear.<br>
<br>
Da armor pieces den came flying straight at Bash.  Bash closed his eyes before da impact hit him.  Nothing happened.  He opened his eyes and found himself covered from head to toe in da beautiful platemail.  He grinned.<br>
<br>
Bash den felt his hammer, his helmet, his breastplate, his pants, everyting, get berry warm.<br>
<br>
"Do not be afraid.  The armor must test you.  It must know your heart to accept you." said da bear.<br>
<br>
-----<br>
<br>
All throughout da underground caverns, an ogre's scream of pain resonated loudly.</p>
