<i>Posted by Numbuk on 04-19-2001 09:25 PM:</i>

<p><b> Chapter 48.</b></p>

<p>Da doors of da cell slammed shut as Lilting, da last of da group, was hurled inside.  Da halfling slammed into da rock wall and fell down into da straw-covered floor.  It took many, many dwarves to subdue Bash and get him chained up inside da cell, but dey eventually did it.  Everyone sat wit long, depressed looks in da gigantic, poorly lit cell.<br>
<br>
Lilting came to consciousness and immediately tried to cast several spells.  All of dem just made a fizzling sound a couple sparks sputtered from his fingertips.<br>
<br>
"It's no use," said Pyra.  "This cell somehow prevents the  use of all magic.  Believe me, I've tried."<br>
<br>
Indeed she did.  Pyra's pyromaniac instincts no could resist such an abundance of clean, dry, flammable straw.<br>
<br>
Bash's stomach began to rumble, dis rumble so loud and powerful dat it made Bash's chains jingle from da low frequency bass.<br>
<br>
"Me huuuungry!" Bash wailed.  He no could take da smell of so much good food around him.  Da ogre's eyes were almost glazed.  It was as if Bash no longer realized what was going on around him, like he was in a trance.<br>
<br>
Rubbing his head, Lilting wondered what dey could do about deir situation and his large friend.  <br>
<br>
"Hey, I know what we can do!" da halfing exclaimed.<br>
<br>
Everyone's eyes turned toward da halfing wit hopefulness.<br>
<br>
"We can play 'Get to Know You'!  You know, we each take a turn telling a bit about ourselves so we each can learn a bit more about each other!  Pretty neat huh?!"  Lilting began bouncing wit excitement.<br>
<br>
"That's a terrible idea!" grumbled a voice from almost underneath da druid.  Everyone turned to see da straw shift and an aging half-elf sat up from being buried in da straw.  Da half-elf's long, matted hair was almost all gray.  What little color remained was undeterminable from all da grime.<br>
<br>
Treehugger looked at da half-elf and thought dat he looked somehow familiar, but den soon dismissed da thought.  "If you have a better suggestion than the halfling's, old man, then I say spit them out!  Who are you anyway to raise your voice to my friend?"<br>
<br>
Da old half-elf spat.  "Quit your condescending attitude, boy!  You've likely not gained nearly as much life experience as I!"  And den he mumbled under his breath, "<i>Or as many women either, from the looks of you</i>."  And went back to speaking in an audible tone.  "My name is unimportant in this hell hole, just as yours will be in time.  Yours will be too, eventually.   Those on the outside who know you will soon forget you, and then this thing you call life will suddenly have been pointless!  But, if you must address me, I guess the name 'Bob' is as good as any."<br>
<br>
Treehugger squinted at da older man wit distrust and dislike.<br>
<br>
Lilting piped up.  "Well, we won't be in here that long, Bob!  We're supposed to be executed pretty soon!"<br>
<br>
"A fate I wish I would have gotten years ago," sighed Bob.<br>
<br>
"Anyway, '<i>Bob</i>'," began Treehugger again wit much sarcasm, "If you have a better idea to pass the time than my friend's here I suggest you let us know it!"<br>
<br>
Bob scowled at da ranger but remained silent.<br>
<br>
"Ok then," said Lilting cheerily.  "Who wants to go first?"<br>
<br>
"Me huuuuungry!" wailed Bash.<br>
<br>
<br>
-------------<br>
<br>
<br>
"Well, I guess it all began with my village." said Lilting quietly.  "You see, everyone there is a druid.  My mom's a druid, my dad's a druid, everyone is a druid.  So, I became a druid too."<br>
<br>
Everyone listened intently to da halfling in da torchlit cell.  Lilting began to sniffle slightly.<br>
<br>
"I realized that everyone had the same notion as to what being a druid is!  They were all greedy, brainless people who thought that the only way to live in this life is to cast a spell and then run away like a coward!  I thought there had to be a better way.  There just has to!"<br>
<br>
Lilting began to cry.<br>
<br>
"It was my backwards way of thinking that got me exiled from my own city."<br>
<br>
Lilting den began to ball like a baby.  Dose nearest to da halfling comforted him reassuringly.<br>
<br>
"I miss my mommy!" Lilting wailed.  <br>
<br>
Da halfling den just kept continuing sobbing.  When he quieted down, Pyra began to speak.<br>
<br>
"My family is one of the most prominent and powerful families in all of Erudin.  Yes, that means that my father and mother were..."<br>
<br>
"King and queen?" Lilting interjected quickly, while snorting back some loosened phlegm from his crying.<br>
<br>
"Governors?" asked Bob.<br>
<br>
"No."  Pyra said.  "They were cheesemakers.  As you may or may not know, Erudins love cheese.  They crave it!  Gouda, pepperjack, mozarella, cheddar, we love it all.  We cannot get enough of it.  There is a saying, 'He who controls the cheese, controls the empire!  The cheese must flow.'<br>
<br>
"Yes," said Bob.  "I've heard that some people say the Erudin's brainpower...<i>and overdeveloped heads</i>," Bob muttered, "are the result of their high intake of cheese."<br>
<br>
"Yes, many believe that." Pyra said quietly.  "We don't know the cause, we just know we love cheese.  Anyway, my parents were cheesemakers.  I, of course, delighted in setting things on fire.  It was because of this that I accidentally set the cheese factory ablaze.<br>
<br>
"To make a long story short, melted cheese three feet deep covered the entire town of Erudin for a while.  My parents sent me to go see a therapist about controlling my firestarting ways.  But, I instead chose to play hookie.<br>
<br>
"That is when I met you guys."<br>
<br>
Da group looked at each udder nervously after hearing dis tale; except for Bash, of course.<br>
<br>
"And we're so glad you're here, Pyra!" said Treehugger very quickly.  Da ranger's eyes darted around frantically as he wrung his hands.  He den decided to try and shift da uneasiness everyone was feeling onto someone else.  He turned to Medsa.<br>
<br>
"And how about you, hot stuff?"</p>
<hr>
<i>Posted by Numbuk on 06-06-2001 09:48 PM:</i>

<p><b> Chapter 49.</b></p>

<p>"Why does everyone want to know about me?" demanded Medsa hotly.  Da High Elf cleric became rather defensive when Lilting prodded about her past.<br>
<br>
"Because it's your turn!" said da halfling excitedly.  "We all agreed to talk about our pasts.  We were going in a counter-clockwise circle, so now it's fallen on you!"<br>
<br>
"Well I didn't agree to it!" Medsa said wit a scowl.<br>
<br>
"But..."<br>
<br>
"Just leave me alone!  I don't want to talk about anything!  Ask me one more time and you'll see just how mean I can get!"  Da cleric's eyes shone down on Lilting like daggers.  Lilting  immediately shut up and looked genuinely afraid.<br>
<br>
Treehugger spoke up and broke da tension.  "If the lady doesn't want to talk about her past, then let's respect it.  Ok, guys?"<br>
<br>
Medsa's frown and scowl turned towards da ranger.  She looked at Treehugger and for a second it seemed like her iron face softened a little bit, but den she turned around and sat in one of da cell corners.  She folded her arms and looked away from da group, staring at nothing in particular.<br>
<br>
After da long silence, Sir Yessir slammed his hands together and began rubbing them in eager  anticipation.<br>
<br>
"Is it my turn, good sir halfling?" da knight asked.<br>
<br>
"Sure!  If you want it to be!" said Lilting, perking up again.<br>
<br>
"Oh, great is my joy!" da paladin said delightfully wit a smile.  Da knight stood up, armor creaking and squeaking as he did so, and assumed a public speaking stance.<br>
<br>
"As you all know, I am a professional dragonslayer.  I was not born this way, though!  Oh no.  Ye see, dragonslayers are rare in this world.  They are chosen people at birth by the gods and are endowed with the gift of being able to single-handedly destroy the reptilian beasts."<br>
<br>
"I've heard of lots of people taking out dragons," said Pyra.  "Does this mean they were all born dragonslayers?"<br>
<br>
"Oh heavens no!  Ye've heard of dragon raids, I am sure.  These always consist of an insane amount of people, many of which are killed quickly.  What they never tell you is.... that all the dragons they are able to kill are the weakest and sickliest of the dragon species!  Sure, they don't look weak or sick but dragons aren't people, ye know?<br>
<br>
"Anyways, I was not a born dragonslayer.  As a young boy, I was playing outside of our tiny little shack.  While doing so, a mean, nasty, baby dragon scurried across the yard and bit me in the leg.  It hurt.  A lot!  I was so upset, that I chased that dragon.  I chased it for three days.  Finally I caught up to it and an epic battle ensued!  After another four days, I came out victorious!"<br>
<br>
"How old were you?" asked Lilting.<br>
<br>
"Two and a half years old.  It was then that I vowed to make sure that no more dragons were to ever live to hurt another human being again!  I also vowed to invent a better diaper, but that one didn't pan out as well as I had planned.  But I digress, I couldn't find my way back home.  I began to wander.<br>
<br>
"I eventually found myself on the doorstep to a paladin's guild.  I still had a hard time reaching doorknobs, so I did the universal action for help for people my age.  I cried.  I screamed my lungs out!<br>
<br>
"After about nine days of that, the paladins eventually broke down and let me in just to shut me up.  My plan had worked!  I trained with those knights, learning everything I could as the years went on.  Not only did I teach myself how to slay dragons, but I made sure that each and every dragon that came into the paladin's garden was destroyed!  Those fellows never had a dragon problem again.<br>
<br>
"After several years, and after I had destroyed half of the guild in a botched dragon experiment, the paladins asked me to leave.  They told me I was becoming.... how did they put it?  'Too powerful, smart, and skillful to learn anything else from them.'  My, those knights were so kind to me!  They even booted me out onto the street with their weakest kicker.<br>
<br>
"I then became a freelance dragonslayer.  I roamed the countryside looking for dragons to slay.  It was a double-bonus for me!  I would gain skill and knowledge how to slay dragons with each fight, and I'd also be ridding the world of the pesky things!  And after many slayings, I finally bump into you guys.  The end!"<br>
<br>
Yessir took a long bow.  His armor squeaked as he bent down, but dere was also a loud *SNAP* dat seemed to come from his back region.  Dere was just silence from everyone as he made his bow.  Lilting began clapping intensely and cheering.  Da halfling loved da story.  Da knight straightened himself back up after much negotiating wit his spine.<br>
<br>
Nobody said much of anyting for several minutes.  Da silence was broken when Bash, still staring blankly, screamed.<br>
<br>
<b>"Me HUUUUUUUUNNNNNNGGGRRYYYYYYY!!!!!!!!"</b><FONT face="arial, helvetica" size="2"><br>
__________________<br>
<a href="http://eqforge.com/profiles/profile.cfm?ID=4661" target="_blank">Numbuk Rangerfriend</a><br>
Ogre Ranger/Musician/Writer<br>
Read da bestest story of all time <a href="http://forums.interealms.com/ranger/showthread.php?s=9107eacad28b4aac27f93ee6fa196c94&threadid=13422" target="_blank">here</a>!</font></p>
<hr>
<i>Posted by Numbuk on 06-27-2001 09:01 PM:</i>

<p><b> Chapter 50.</b></p>

<p>Everyone was asleep in da dark cell.  Berry, berry loud and deep snoring could be heard coming from Bash's direction, but close inspection showed dat da snoring did not come from da ogre but da druid Lilting.  Da only udder noises heard were da mumblings of a sleeping Bash about starving, and da crackle of da torchlight in da hallway outside of da cell.<br>
<br>
Medsa was still awake sitting in a corner, hugging her knees to her chest and staring at da ground.  Da cleric looked a bit a bit sad while she thought.<br>
<br>
"Still awake?" a voice whispered.<br>
<br>
Medsa looked up to see dat Treehugger had come over to where she sat.  She didn't say a word and den went back to looking at da ground.<br>
<br>
Da ranger sat down next to her.  He didn't say anyting for a few minutes.  Finally da half-elf spoke again.<br>
<br>
"Listen, don't worry about those guys.  They didn't mean to pressure you into anything.  They just want you to be a part of the group.  They didn't mean to make you upset.  They just..."<br>
<br>
"It's not that!" da cleric whispered curtly.  "It's...  Oh you wouldn't understand!"<br>
<br>
"Try me." Da ranger looked at da high-elf wit sadness.  He didn't like to see her in pain.<br>
<br>
Medsa made a scowling face as she looked at da ground.  After several more minutes she spoke again.<br>
<br>
"I hurt."<br>
<br>
"What's wrong?!  What happened?!"<br>
<br>
"It's not a physical pain.  Oh, how I wish it were!  I could cure that instantly."  Medsa's face became sad.  "All my life I've had problems dealing with people.  I tend to be a bit brash with them and eventually they see me as some ticked-off witch and leave me alone.  I've never even had a real friend."<br>
<br>
Treehugger looked at dis lady and couldn't understand how anyone could not be her friend.  Da ranger wanted to say so much, but he was smart enough to be quiet at dis moment.<br>
<br>
"I'm not a mean person on the inside.  I just don't know how to show that to people.  I try to, but it always seem to come out as insults.  Nobody even looks at me as a person anymore.  All they see is a resource that can heal them up so they can go off fighting again.<br>
<br>
"Then I meet you guys.  You guys have treated me better than anyone in my entire life and look I repay you.  I don't say much and when I do I insult everyone.  I haven't even done anything for this group and yet here I am.  It's only a matter of time before you guys get sick of me too and leave me."<br>
<br>
Treehugger snapped at dat.  He reached out his arm and pulled her face gently, but sharply towards him so dat she had to look at da ranger as he spoke.<br>
<br>
"How can you say that?!  This group came alive the minute you joined!  Nobody here hates you!"<br>
<br>
"But I haven't even done anything worthwhile!  I've just been tagging along!"<br>
<br>
Treehugger gazed into her eyes caringly and den softly spoke.  "You saved my life."<br>
<br>
"Yeah, and that's the only reason why you pay any attention to me."  Medsa tried to look away but Treehugger made sure she didn't.<br>
<br>
"If you truly believed that, then the pain I would feel would be far greater than anything that demon did to me.<br>
<br>
"I don't care what you think others think of you.  I know what I think of you.  I see a wonderful lady.  Maybe one who could work on her social skills a little bit, but a wonderful beautiful lady nonetheless.  Believe me or don't believe me.  But I know what I think."<br>
<br>
Treehugger took his hand away and placed it on da ground.  He turned his head away and started into nothingness in frustration.  Medsa looked downward, deep in thought.<br>
<br>
After several long, silent minutes da cleric's hand found it's way on top of Treehugger's.<br>
<br>
"Tell me," Medsa began, "what made you decide to become an excellent swordsman."<br>
<br>
Da ranger clasped da cleric's hand gently, he turned his head and smiled at her.<br>
<br>
"Well, first off, I'm not all that great of a swordsman.  And secondly, it was one man who made me attempt to be good at the blades.  The Geistmeister."<br>
<br>
"Who's that?"<br>
<br>
"He's a legend amongst us rangers.  He was the greatest swordsman to have ever lived.  It was said that nothing could defeat him!  He was a whirlwind of death."<br>
<br>
"And you've met this guy?"<br>
<br>
"No.  Not really.  I saw him once when I was very, very young.  He singlehandedly saved Kelethin from the first and last massive orc invasion.  He was amazing to watch.  I knew then that if I could be as good as him, then I would never have to worry about being afraid for my own life.<br>
<br>
"Unfortunately, I never did get that good.  I'm terrible with the swords!  It's only a matter of time before I get killed.  If I were anything like the Geistmeister..."<br>
<br>
"Bah!" a voice snorted from underneath some nearby hay.  Da cleric and ranger turned towards da sound.  Da hay shifted and up sat deir inmate, Bob.  Pieces of hay stuck out of his scraggly beard and hair.<br>
<br>
"The Geistmeister!  What a load of hooey.  He wasn't all that great!"<br>
<br>
"What do you know, you unkempt bum?!  He was the better with the blades than any other person!"<br>
<br>
"That is correct."<br>
<br>
"But you said he wasn't all that great!"<br>
<br>
"That is also correct.  You see boy, his skill was indeed unmatched by anybody.  He had the talent, but he lacked focus.  He let his pride cloud his thinking.  He trusted too much in his ability with his steel than his ability with his heart and mind.  That eventually led to his downfall."<br>
<br>
"Whatever!  He's the greatest there ever was, nobody would be able to take him down!"<br>
<br>
"Is that so?  Well then, tell me boy, where is this fellow?  Hmmmm?  There was a man who could 'take him down.'  And that man was himself."<br>
<br>
"But, how could that be for a man who could solo the Avatar of Fear?"<br>
<br>
"Bah, that wussy little avatar wasn't that big a deal.  He was more brawn than brain."<br>
<br>
"Or the time he cleared all the giants out of Greater Faydark by himself?"<br>
<br>
"It wasn't that big a deal, really.  Giants tend to get nasty corns on their feet, you just gotta know where to poke."<br>
<br>
"What about the time.... whoa, wait a minute.."  Treehugger started putting two and two together.<br>
<br>
"You're him, aren't you?!"<br>
<br>
Bob nodded.<br>
<br>
Treehugger's eyes became wide open.  "There's so much I want to ask you...!!"<br>
<br>
"Later. You haven't much time left here.  Now listen to me, the both of you.  I've had a lot of time to think in this cell here and reflect on my life.  I've learned that a skill does not make you who you are.  You do.  I look at you both and I see two people lacking confidence in themselves.  You have to learn that it is not what the world thinks of you that makes you important or special, it's what you think of yourself.  The best thing I've learned while in here is: Whether you think you can or whether you think you can't, you're right.<br>
<br>
"Try to remember this, young ones.  I will have to see you both again another time."<br>
<br>
"Wait," said Treehugger.  "How is it that you haven't escaped from here?  Surely you could do so!"<br>
<br>
"Of course I could.  But that wouldn't have done me much good.  You can't escape from yourself.  Like I said, I had to figure myself out and this seemed the best place to do so.  Learn from my mistakes, please.  I wish you the best."<br>
<br>
"But..."  Treehugger was cut short by da sound of an iron door slamming shut.  Several armed dwarven guards had entered da hallway outside of da cell.<br>
<br>
"Get up, you traitors!" shouted one of da guards as another began opening the cell door.  "It's time for your execution!"</p>
<hr>
<i>Posted by Numbuk on 07-06-2001 10:24 PM:</i>

<p><b> Chapter 51.</b></p>

<p>Hundreds of dwarves sat in the underground arena seats looking down towards da center.  On a huge wooden stand, Bash's entire party were each bent over a chopping block.  Dere was a hooded dwarf to each member, and each dwarf wielded a huge, two-handed axe.  Da dwarven spectators talked excitedly amongst each udder.<br>
<br>
Den King Kazon appeared from out behind one of da main doors.  All da dwarves began to clap and show a little enthusiasm.  Den Queen Nozak and da Royal Seer appeared.  Da hundreds of dwarves stood and cheered so loud dat it made Lilting's ears ring.  Da king held up a hand to silence everyone.<br>
<br>
"What we have here are big meanie traitors!" Kazon shouted.<br>
<br>
Da crowd began to Boo at da party.  Bash no heard any of it.  Da king had come and stood right next to da big ogre.  Kazon had been eating extra fried food dis morning, so his beard and skin were covered in chicken and onion ring grease.  Da ogre's eyes were so glazed one wondered if he had any pupils at all.  His stomach was vibrating so hard dat it made his platemail ring.<br>
<br>
"These mean meanies sent that other big, black meanie who destroyed most of our city!" da king shouted.  Everyone booed louder.  Da Seer looked over at da Queen sorrowfully, and da Queen just shook her head and sighed.<br>
<br>
"For this reason," da king shouted some more, "I order that they be put to death by having their heads cut off in the un-nicest fashion!"<br>
<br>
Everyone roared wit approval and applause.<br>
<br>
Dough dey were tied down, many of da party members could still turn deir head a little bit to see what was going on.  Treehugger looked at Medsa.  To see her da way she was and knowing what was about to happen angered him berry much.  He struggled against his cords wit all his might, but he could not break dem.  Da cleric just looked back at da ranger and shed a single tear.<br>
<br>
Everyone was pretty frightened, well, except for Bash.  Da ogre seemed so distant.  Sir Yessir also didn't show much fear either.  He seemed content just smiling and humming some old tune.<br>
<br>
Pyra tried her best to light the rope or the wooden platform on fire, but for some reason her magic did not seem to work.  Da situation for everyone looked grim.<br>
<br>
"So what say you?" da king yelled.  "Do they live, or die?"<br>
<br>
All da dwarves started stomping deir feet and chanting in unison.  "DIE!  DIE!  DIE!  DIE!"<br>
<br>
"I thought as much!  Besides, I was going to kill them anyway!" All da dwarves laughed and cheered at da comment.<br>
<br>
"Very well then!  Guards, kill them!  Kill them now in the meanest way for the big meanies!"<br>
<br>
Simultaneously, all da hooded dwarves raised deir axes high over deir heads.  Treehugger kept his eyes on Medsa.  He saw her executioner tense his muscles, ready to swing da axe home.  Da ranger screamed da most rage-filled scream anyone had ever heard.<br>
<br>
Many of da onlooking dwarves were a little confused, and some scared.  But da king motioned to da guards to continue.<br>
<br>
And dat is when it happened....  All of a sudden, da ground shook slightly.<br>
<br>
Da spectators looked confused once again and began talking amongst demselves nervously.  Kazon, getting upset at interruptions, motioned again.<br>
<br>
Da ground shook again, dis time a bit stronger.   Den it continued to shake until rocks and stalagtites fell from da cavern ceiling.  Da dwarves started to scream in panic.<br>
<br>
All of a sudden, from da middle of da arena, rocks exploded apart from da ground sending rubble flying everywhere.  Out smashed a big black form crashing through part of da wooden stage.<br>
<br>
Raising his glowing brown claymore high and shaking in rage, da Black Guardian, Earth, had come back to finish da deed he had been ordered.</p>
<hr>
<i>Posted by Numbuk on 07-12-2001 10:57 PM:</i>

<p><b> Chapter 52.</b></p>

<p>Hundreds of dwarves scattered about as pieces of rock and debris flew everywhere.  Earth concentrated on wiping out as many of da little guys as possible, as well as any buildings dat da Guardian had missed on it's last visit to Kaladim.<br>
<br>
Da Elemental Guardian would kick, punch, and slash da dwarves sending many to deir deaths.  Sometimes a dwarf would escape da knight's blows, but Earth had a way of dealing wit dem.  Da Black Knight would slam it's sword downward and da blade would sink into da hard rock floor as if it were slicing through soft dirt.  When da knight did dis, da rock would reshape and da knight seemed to have limited control of da cavern itself.  A pillar of rock would shoot out of da ground, carrying a dwarf or dwarves skyward until it slammed into da cavern ceiling.  Da pillar would den sink back downward and reshape back to it's original rock form.  Many dwarven bloodstains matted da once beautiful, hand-carved ceiling.<br>
<br>
Da dwarves, though scattering, fought back against da knight.   Dey were dwarves after all, and dwarves are a hardy, stubborn bunch.  Dey hated uninvited guests.  Dey fought valiantly, but none were able to even visibly hurt da seemingly invulnerable knight.  Da more dey fought back, da more powerful da knight seemed to get.  Da battle looked hopeless, but still dey fought on.<br>
<br>
---------<br>
<br>
Da wooden platform dat da party was on now creaked and shuddered.  Many of da legs dat had held it up had been destroyed or severely damage.  It tilted downward and continued to slowly pitch forward slightly, pointing da party directly into da black hole da knight had exploded from.<br>
<br>
Lilting had noticed a peg dat held one of his cords had been damaged.  Da halfling struggled and flexed his tiny muscles.  Da rope tightened and he felt da peg begin to give.  He pulled harder.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, da peg broke apart and sent da rope flying.  Lilting was able to pull out his tiny, tiny, oh-so tiny dagger and cut away at da udder cords holding him down.   It was slow going, because his dagger was so toothpick-size tiny.<br>
<br>
Da platform began creak and shudder again as it continued to pitch forward, ready to plummet da party to a seemingly bottomless grave.  Treehugger felt da ropes around his chest and da back of his neck tighten as gravity pulled his body forward.  He looked at Medsa.  Da cleric was terrified.<br>
<br>
Da ranger pulled hard to release himself but he could not make his bondaged situation any better.  He looked at Medsa again.  Da half-elf screamed in anger dat he could do nothing.<br>
<br>
Treehugger den felt a small, fast, vibration on da back of his wrist.  He turned his head around as much as he could and saw Lilting sawing away like mad wit his tiny, tiny, sewing needle of a dagger.<br>
<br>
"Lilting!" Treehugger yelled in delight.<br>
<br>
"Yeah!  I know!  I'm trying to hurry!"<br>
<br>
Da platform began to pick up speed in tilting forward as da weight of da group had shifted to da forefront.<br>
<br>
Treehugger pulled hard against da frayed part of da rope da halfling had made by his sawing.  Da rope snapped and ranger's hands became free.  He threw da rest of da ropes overhead easily escaping.<br>
<br>
"Lilting, there's not enough time for you to save everyone!  I need something sharp and I need  it now!"<br>
<br>
Treehugger quickly scanned da room.  Amidst all da fighting, he saw a display table nearby da arena doors.  On it were several items, including...<br>
<br>
"My swords!" da ranger yelled.  "Lilting, go get em quick!"<br>
<br>
Lilting began chanting really fast.  "Spirits of wolf come to me, make my feet as fast as fast can be!"  Da halfling's feet shot out blue sparks and Lilting sped off like a bolt of lightning.<br>
<br>
Da ranger jumped to da back of da tilted platform to try and counter some of da weight.  It was useless, as much of it was from Bash.  Treehugger dropped carefully by Medsa and did his best to undo da knots dat kept her bound.  He strained, but it was no use.  Da knots were too tight.<br>
<br>
"Treehugger!" shouted a blur.  Lilting had come by so fast da halfling was next to him before da voice had caught up wit him.  Lilting held out da ranger's swords.<br>
<br>
"Get Pyra!" excalimed da ranger.  Da halfling bolted in a flash over to da wizardess.<br>
<br>
Lilting sawed like mad against da ropes dat held da erudite down.  Once one of her hands was free, she easily set da rest of her ropes on fire.  Pyra easily broke free as da ropes became instantly weak and charred.  Both she and da halfling went to Yessir was right next to dem.<br>
<br>
"How rude!" said da paladin as da halfling and wizardess worked quickly to release him.  "How rude of that big black guy to come and ruin a perfectly good and planned out execution!  I really hate party crashers!  Almost as much as I hate dragons!"<br>
<br>
Da platform now was rapidly tipping forward and da group had but mere seconds to get off of it.  Treehugger slashed three times at da cleric, and da ropes dat tied her down were perfectly cut and Medsa had not even been touched by da ranger's swords.  He pulled her up.<br>
<br>
"Jump!" he said.<br>
<br>
"What?" asked da cleric.<br>
<br>
"Jump off to the ground!  There isn't much time!  I need to rescue Bash!"<br>
<br>
Medsa glanced nervously about, but nodded and ran up to da back of da platform, and jumped to safety.<br>
<br>
Da fire from da ropes dat Pyra had started quickly spread to da rest of da platform.  Lilting, Yessir, and Pyra worked frantically to get Bash free.  Da ogre did not try to help break da cords, but still lay dere staring blankly.<br>
<br>
Treehugger leaped through da flames.  Da platform was fastly approaching da point of no return.<br>
<br>
"Jump off!" shouted da ranger.  "Jump off now and I will save him!"  Treehugger pointed one of his swords off to da side of da platform for da three of dem to jump.  Without hesitation, dey did.<br>
<br>
"Come on big guy, help me out here!" pleaded da ranger.  He sliced da ropes free and da ogre began to slide forward.<br>
<br>
"Oh no you don't!" said da ranger.  He grabbed onto da big ogre's wrist and tried to pull him back.  He slowed down da shaman, but 600 pounds of ogre is not an easy ting to stop.  He pulled wit all his half-elf might to try and get him back up da platform and drag him to safety.<br>
<br>
Medsa watched helplessly as da ranger and shaman teetered at da berry edge of da chasm.  She looked pleadingly to da rest of da party, but dey all looked back at her wit da same bit of helplessness.<br>
<br>
She watched and saw dat da ranger was making some progress sliding bash to da side of da platform.  If he could just get Bash over to da edge...<br>
<br>
Den, da raging fire caused one of da few supporting legs of da platform to crack and shift.  Da whole platform broke apart and tumbled forward, taking da ranger and ogre wit it.  Medsa stared in shock as she watched Treehugger and Bash disappear wit da burning debris into da black abyss.</p>
